Another approach would be to read the configuration file and store the name/value pairs in a Hashtable.

If the order in which the settings appear in the text file is not important, you could use the `ConvertFrom-StringData` cmdlet.
This will parse the settings names and values and returns it as Hashtable.

    $config = Get-Content -Path .\configuration.txt -Raw | ConvertFrom-StringData

If the order **DOES** matter, create an ordered hash (needs PowerShell 3.0 or better):

    $config  = [ordered]@{}
    Get-Content -Path D:\configuration.txt | ForEach-Object {
        $name, $value = ($_ -split &#39;=&#39; , 2).Trim()
        $config[$name] = $value
    }

If the user wants to change the value of `Setting1` to `no` for instance ($UserSetting1=&#39;no&#39;), simply do:

    $UserSetting1 = &#39;no&#39;
    $config.Setting1 = $UserSetting1

    # Next save the updated settings back to the textfile
    $newContent = foreach($name in $config.Keys) {
        &#39;{0} = {1}&#39; -f $name, $config.$name
    }
    $newContent | Set-Content -Path .\configuration.txt -Force

